{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491457"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"943"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/943"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.38,0.01,0,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/943"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16386"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1039"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13416"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 72-year-old woman presents with a two-day history of increasing crampy and generalised abdominal pain. This is associated with nausea, abdominal distension and constipation. Her medical history includes an hysterectomy. Her abdomen is distended and soft. Some faecal pellets are felt on rectal examination. A plain X-ray is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adhesive small bowel obstruction","Gallstone ileus","Appendicitis","Renal colic","Pseudo-obstruction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows gas in the small bowel. Whilst there are usually small volumes of gas in the small intestine, the X-ray shows more gas than usual and dilated loops of bowel. This is small bowel distension, based on the observation of a central distribution of the bowel loops and the presence of valvulae conniventes - mucosal folds going fully across the lumen. Pseudo-obstruction involves the large bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is also a large (5 x 3 cm) oval calcified lesion in the right side of the abdomen. Whilst this could (almost) be in the right renal tract, its smooth outline suggests another cause. Whilst faecoliths (appendicitis) can calcify, they are never more than about 1 cm diameter. This area of calcification is almost certainly a gallstone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture fits for small bowel obstruction and whilst the commonest cause is adhesive-obstruction, the presence of the gallstone would suggest that the diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E. \u0027Ileus\u0027 is a misnomer as the dynamic is a mechanical obstruction and not gut inactivity. Prior to the regular use of CT scanning, most cases of gallstone ileus were diagnosed at the time of surgery, rather than pre-operatively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gallstone ileus is a rare, but well recognised, cause of small bowel obstruction."],"references":["Catena F, De Simone B, Coccolini F, et al. Bowel obstruction: a narrative review for all physicians. World J Emerg Surg. 2019; 14:20."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16386"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"943"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18394"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18394","links":{"self":"https:/